<br>
Inside, Aryllyian burns with a desire to react violently to this rogue's outlandish and self absorbing desires.  Projecting a calmness bought through many seasons of loss, Aryllyian's eyes clearly express the sadness of a passing friend.  To Ary the Rogue has suddenly become Elthoeill (an elven concept of outsider)<br>
<br>
Aryllyian's world is black and white.  You are either friend or foe.  As Myrrer slips into the shadows, Ary whispers,  &quot;So it comes to this, old friend....May Tunare stay my wrath and May Bristlebane lead you to righteousness&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#BA9F70><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite.showUserPublicProfile?gid=firinn>Firinn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Raid Leader / BFB</span><br>  Posts: 411<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(12/17/02 2:59:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=90.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Temptation of a Rogue</span><hr size=1>      Its late in the guildhall, quiet and subdued.  A large painted barbarian sits in the corner, facing the wall, engaged in ritual.  Firinn sits in the darkness, in silence, slow gestures are made, his head head slightly turned, as if listening, his eyes open, staring into the infinite darkess.  <br>
     A soft voice ripples the silence, &quot;Hello, bear.&quot;<br>
    &quot;Hello, rogue.&quot; the shaman responds, without turning.<br>
    &quot;I've come to seek council, Firinn.  My heart is burdened with choices I wish I did not have to make.&quot;<br>
    Firinn rises and turns to face the rogue, looking down he studies Myrrer's face for a moment, and then sits.  &quot;Lets talk friend, tell me of your troubles.&quot;<br>
    Myrrer explains the calling of Bristlebane, the very calling of adventure, that draws him to the lands of Tunare.  They talk of the fantastic possibilities of exploring a new land, the excitement and the anticipation of the unknown, and the possibility of great reward.  The rogue explains his dilema, his call to adventure, and his loyalty to his friends.  He knows that an act of aggression against Tunare will be a violation of trust with his friends, though he does not feel their devotion to Tunare.  They talk of possibilities, of adventures past, and adventures yet to come.<br>
    &quot;Myrrer, my friend and companion, I fear you will find the Elves intolerant of trangressions against Tunare.  Many are followers of Tunare, and cannot fathom what it is you are considering.  Know that I cannot fault your inclination; as it serves your lord Bristlebane, if only for the adventure, and, I believe it serves your very nature.  Though, you may find the rewards do not outweigh the loss, you may also find other association more suited to your wanderings.  No matter which you choose, your are always welcome in my company.  Also know, that if you stay, you may still satisfy your lord Bristlebane with great adventures in the company of Elves, though you will never hunt the realm of Tunare.  I do not envy the choice before you, friend, but I do hope you will decide to keep this guildhall as your home.&quot;<br>
    With that, they both stand.  Firinn once again looks down on his friends face, frowns, and then smiles.  &quot;Safe journey to you rogue, it is time for me to rest.  Do let me know what you decide.&quot;  The barbarian turns and walks away.<br>
